The Geometric Eigenvalue of \mathbf{m = 1.878}: Unifying Cosmological Tension and Galactic Dynamics in Motion-TimeSpace Theory

Abstract
The Motion-TimeSpace (MTS) framework provides a unified, geometry-based resolution to the core problems in modern cosmology and galactic dynamics: the Hubble Tension and the lack of dark matter observables. This paper synthesizes the empirical discovery of a Universal Mass Exponent, \mathbf{m = 1.878 \pm 0.003}, in the radial stellar mass profiles (M(r) \propto r^m) of mature spiral galaxies with the first-principles derivation from the governing MTS Field Equation We demonstrate that \mathbf{m = 1.878} is not a fitted parameter but a Geometric Eigenvalue—the unique, stable state achieved when the two fundamental MTS field constants, Curvature Stiffness (\mathbf{\Lambda_\kappa}) and Dissipative Resistance (\mathbf{\Gamma_\kappa}), reach a state of dynamic and static equilibrium.

1. Introduction: Beyond the $\mathbf{\Lambda}$CDM Crisis
Standard \LambdaCDM cosmology is challenged by two severe, high-significance tensions: the persistent failure to model galaxy rotation curves without introducing non-baryonic Dark Matter (DM) and the ongoing Hubble Tension (\mathbf{H_0}). 
The \mathbf{MTS} theory posits that the phenomena attributed to DM and \mathbf{\Lambda} are instead the observable geometric effects of a non-linear, dynamic spacetime field. 
The core of MTS is the Motion-TimeSpace Field Equation (MEFE), which introduces two new fundamental constants to the geometric side of the equation:
Here, \mathbf{\kappa_{\mu\nu}} is the Motion-TimeSpace field tensor, governed by:
.	Curvature Stiffness (\mathbf{\Lambda_\kappa}): Defines the intrinsic, static tension of the spacetime vacuum, responsible for long-range screening.
.	Dissipative Resistance (\mathbf{\Gamma_\kappa}): A kinematic damping constant governing the field's reaction to velocity and dynamics, responsible for cosmic expansion and local instability.


