4.2. Unifying the Static and Dynamic Constraints
The Dissipative Resistance (\mathbf{\Gamma_\kappa}) dictates the following:
1.	Cosmology: It drives the time-evolutionary correction \mathbf{\alpha_1} necessary to resolve the \mathbf{H_0} Tension.
2.	Galactic Scale: It establishes the Kinematic Instability Corridor (\mathbf{v_c \approx 100 \text{ km s}^{-1}}).
3.	Threshold: It defines the mass/velocity threshold below which systems are dominated by dynamic chaos and fail to settle into the stable \mathbf{m = 1.878} state defined by \mathbf{\Lambda_\kappa}.
Therefore, the two fundamental parameters of the MEFE, \mathbf{\Lambda_\kappa} and \mathbf{\Gamma_\kappa}, conspire to establish the conditions for the existence and stability of the \mathbf{m = 1.878} exponent.

5. Conclusion: The Power of a Single Geometric Constant
The discovery and derivation of \mathbf{m = 1.878} serve as the most compelling structural evidence for the MTS framework. This exponent is not a free parameter—it is the Geometric Eigenvalue of the frameworks field equations.

1.	Inevitable Structure: Any gravitating system that evolves beyond the dynamic threshold set by \mathbf{\Gamma_\kappa} must settle into the geometric configuration defined by \mathbf{m = 1.878} to minimize its internal geometric stress against the vacuum tension (\mathbf{\Lambda_\kappa}).
2.	Falsifiability: The MTS theory makes a strong, testable prediction: the two geometric constants derived from galactic dynamics (\mathbf{m=1.878} and \mathbf{v_c \approx 100 \text{ km s}^{-1}}) are precisely the constants required to resolve the \mathbf{H_0} Tension and model galaxy rotation curves without Dark Matter.
The universal mass exponent \mathbf{m = 1.878} is the geometric fingerprint of a non-linear, dynamic spacetime—a constant of nature that unifies the large-scale structure of the Universe with the structure of individual galaxies.


